SENATE BILL 483
E2 6lr2087
CF HB 360
By: Senators McKay, Smith, Sydnor, Waldstreicher, Love, and Muse
Introduced and read first time: February 2, 2026
Assigned to: Judicial Proceedings
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: March 4, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Criminal Procedure – Automated Expungement Shielding
3 (Clean Slate Act of 2026)
4 FOR the purpose of requiring the Department of Public Safety and Correctional Services
5 and the Judiciary to expunge shield all cases meeting certain criteria on or before a
6 certain date; requiring the Department and the Judiciary to expunge shield certain
7 newly eligible cases on a monthly basis; and generally relating to expungement
8 shielding.
9 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
10 Article – Criminal Procedure
11 Section 10–301(a) through (e)
12 Annotated Code of Maryland
13 (2025 Replacement Volume)
14 BY adding to
15 Article – Criminal Procedure
16 Section 10–112.1 10–303.1
17 Annotated Code of Maryland
18 (2025 Replacement Volume)
19 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
20 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
21 Article – Criminal Procedure
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0483*

2 SENATE BILL 483
1 10–301.
2 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
3 (b) “Court record” has the meaning stated in § 10–101 of this title.
4 (c) “Criminal justice unit” has the meaning stated in § 10–201 of this title.
5 (d) “Police record” has the meaning stated in § 10–101 of this title.
6 (e) “Shield” means to render a court record and police record relating to a
7 conviction of a crime inaccessible by members of the public.
8 10–112.1. 10–303.1.
9 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
10 INDICATED.
11 (2) (I) “DISPOSITION” MEANS THE OUTCOME OF A CRIMINAL
12 CHARGE OR CASE RECORDED IN ELECTRONIC COURT RECORDS.
13 (II) “DISPOSITION” INCLUDES AN ACQUITTAL, A DISMISSAL, A
14 NOLLE PROSEQUI, A FINDING OF GUILTY, A PROBATION BEFORE JUDGMENT, A PLEA
15 OF GUILTY, A PLEA OF NOLO CONTENDERE, MARKING THE CHARGE “STET” ON THE
16 DOCKET, AND AN ORDER OF AN APPELLATE COURT ENDING A CRIMINAL CASE.
17 (III) “DISPOSITION” DOES NOT REFER TO THE OUTCOME OF A
18 CRIMINAL SENTENCE.
19 (3) “EXPUNGE” MEANS TO:
20 (I) REMOVE ALL REFERENCES TO A SPECIFIED CRIMINAL CASE
21 FROM THE CENTRAL REPOSITORY; AND
22 (II) REMOVE FROM PUBLIC VIEW ALL ELECTRONIC COURT
23 RECORDS RELATING TO THE CASE, WITHOUT NEEDING TO REDACT PHYSICAL OR
24 ELECTRONIC DOCUMENTS, RECORDINGS, OR AUDIO OR VISUAL MEDIA.
25 (B) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2028, THE DEPARTMENT AND THE JUDICIARY
26 SHALL EXPUNGE ALL CASES IN WHICH:
27 (1) (I) ALL CHARGES OR DISPOSITIONS IN THE CASE ARE LISTED
28 UNDER § 10–105(A) OF THIS SUBTITLE;

SENATE BILL 483 3
1 (II) THE CASE IS ELIGIBLE UNDER § 10–107 OF THIS SUBTITLE;
2 AND
3 (III) AT LEAST 3 YEARS HAVE PASSED SINCE THE DATE OF THE
4 DISPOSITION OF THE CASE; OR
5 (2) (I) ANY CONVICTIONS IN THE CASE ARE MISDEMEANOR
6 CONVICTIONS LISTED UNDER § 10–110(A) OF THIS SUBTITLE, OTHER THAN:
7 1. ASSAULT IN THE SECOND DEGREE UNDER § 3–203 OF
8 THE CRIMINAL LAW ARTICLE; AND
9 2. ANY CHARGE MARKED IN ELECTRONIC COURT
10 RECORDS AS A DOMESTICALLY RELATED CRIME UNDER § 6–233 OF THIS ARTICLE;
11 (II) THE CASE IS ELIGIBLE UNDER §§ 10–107 AND 10–110(D)(2)
12 AND (3) OF THIS SUBTITLE; AND
13 (III) AT LEAST 7 YEARS HAVE PASSED SINCE THE DISPOSITION OF
14 THE CASE, EXCEPT THAT IF THE PERSON IS CONVICTED OF A NEW CRIME DURING
15 THE 7–YEAR PERIOD, THE ORIGINAL CONVICTION OR CONVICTIONS ARE NOT
16 ELIGIBLE FOR EXPUNGEMENT UNLESS THE NEW CONVICTION BECOMES ELIGIBLE
17 FOR EXPUNGEMENT.
18 (C) (1) BEGINNING AUGUST 1, 2028, THE JUDICIARY SHALL, ONCE PER
19 MONTH, IDENTIFY ALL CASES THAT ARE NEWLY ELIGIBLE FOR EXPUNGEMENT
20 BASED ON THE CRITERIA SET FORTH IN SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION.
21 (2) PROMPTLY AFTER MAKING EACH DETERMINATION REQUIRED
22 UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE JUDICIARY SHALL
23 ELECTRONICALLY NOTIFY THE DEPARTMENT OF ALL CASES THAT ARE NEWLY
24 ELIGIBLE FOR EXPUNGEMENT.
25 (3) WITHIN ONE MONTH OF THE NOTIFICATION REQUIRED UNDER
26 PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE DEPARTMENT AND THE JUDICIARY
27 SHALL EXPUNGE ALL NEWLY ELIGIBLE CASES.
28 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “TECHNICALLY ELIGIBLE FOR EXPUNGEMENT”
29 MEANS THAT, BASED ON THE NATURE OF A CHARGE OR CONVICTION AND THE
30 RELEVANT TIME THAT HAS ELAPSED, A PERSON WOULD BE ELIGIBLE TO FILE A
31 PETITION FOR EXPUNGEMENT UNDER SUBTITLE 1 OF THIS TITLE.

4 SENATE BILL 483
1 (B) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2028, THE JUDICIARY SHALL SHIELD ALL CASES
2 IN WHICH ALL CHARGES IN THE CASE ARE TECHNICALLY ELIGIBLE FOR
3 EXPUNGEMENT.
4 (C) (1) BEGINNING AUGUST 1, 2028, THE JUDICIARY SHALL, ONCE PER
5 MONTH, IDENTIFY ALL CASES IN WHICH ALL CHARGES IN THE CASE ARE NEWLY
6 TECHNICALLY ELIGIBLE FOR EXPUNGEMENT.
7 (2) WITHIN 1 MONTH OF IDENTIFYING A CASE UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)
8 OF THIS SUBSECTION, THE JUDICIARY SHALL SHIELD THE CASE.
9 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
10 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
